{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-04-24T08:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.pcworld.com/article/2752225/this-touchscreen-lenovo-chromebook-doubles-as-a-tablet-and-its-under-80.html", "publishedAt": "2025-04-24T08:00:00Z", "content": "Skip to contentType your search and hit enter\r\nWhen you purchase through links in our articles, we may earn a small commission. This doesn't affect our editorial independence\r\n.\r\nTL;DR: Save over 70%… [+1608 chars]", "title": "This touchscreen Lenovo Chromebook doubles as a tablet, and it’s under $80", "fullContent": "TL;DR: Save over 70% on this Lenovo Chromebook that acts as a laptop and tablet, comes with a touchscreen, and runs on Chrome OS.\n\nLooking for a functional, no-frills device that can keep up with everyday tasks? This refurbished Lenovo 2-in-1 Chromebook hits that sweet spot. It’s lightweight, versatile, and built for basic computing on the go. While supplies last, you can grab your own Lenovo Chromebook for less than $80.\n\nWith its 360-degree hinge, this Chromebook easily flips between laptop and tablet mode, giving you flexibility whether you’re typing out notes or streaming a video. The 11.6-inch HD touchscreen is responsive and compact enough to carry anywhere, making it a solid choice for students, commuters, or anyone who wants a second device for casual use.\n\nSpecs include 4GB of RAM and 32GB of flash storage, which are plenty for web browsing, working in the cloud, or knocking out emails. Powered by Chrome OS, the device boots quickly, is protected from bad actors, and integrates seamlessly with all your favorite Google apps.\n\nRemember how we mentioned this device is refurbished? That accounts for the price tag and how you’re able to score a reliable performance in a near-new device without paying retail price.\n\nIf you’re after a budget-friendly Chromebook that can handle your daily digital grind without slowing you down, this is a smart pickup.\n\nThere are fewer than 50 units left, so grab one of these 11.6-inch Lenovo Chromebooks for just $79.99 while supplies last.\n\nLenovo 300E 11.6″ Touchscreen Chromebook (2018) 4GB RAM 32GB Storage (Refurbished)See Deal\n\nStackSocial prices subject to change."}
{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-04-24T14:23:30Z", "url": "https://www.pcworld.com/article/2763336/microsoft-365-copilot-app-gets-chatgpts-impressive-image-generation.html", "publishedAt": "2025-04-24T14:23:30Z", "content": "Skip to contentType your search and hit enter\r\nWhen you purchase through links in our articles, we may earn a small commission. This doesn't affect our editorial independence\r\n.\r\nMicrosoft has update… [+1516 chars]", "title": "Microsoft 365 Copilot app gets ChatGPT’s impressive image generation", "fullContent": "Microsoft has updated its Microsoft 365 Copilot AI assistant with several new features, The Verge reports. The redesigned Microsoft 365 Copilot app now has access to OpenAI’s impressive GPT-4o model, which was released last month, via Copilot Create. This means you can now generate cutting-edge images, videos, and other content.\n\nAnother big feature update is Notebooks, which are project-based notebooks for organizing information like files, pages, and links, which can then be shared with Copilot. This gives Copilot a more focused collection of context to work with, which then informs its answers when you use Copilot for aid in a given project.\n\nMicrosoft\n\nOther improvements include a better AI search that integrates with third-party platforms like Google Drive, Slack, and Jira; an improved chat interface that now remembers past conversations and can customize responses based on your work patterns and preferences; and an Agent Store for quick access to AI agents from both Microsoft and third parties.\n\nNote that Microsoft 365 Copilot is not the same thing as regular Copilot. The former is intended for business use cases while the latter is for personal use by individual consumers. The two are different, but this update does bring the user interface of Microsoft 365 Copilot more in line with what you’ve likely seen in Copilot itself."}
{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-04-24T14:00:36Z", "url": "https://www.pcworld.com/article/2763187/grab-this-intel-i5-mini-pc-with-24gb-ram-on-sale-now-for-319.html", "publishedAt": "2025-04-24T14:00:36Z", "content": "Skip to contentType your search and hit enter\r\nWhen you purchase through links in our articles, we may earn a small commission. This doesn't affect our editorial independence\r\n.\r\nNowadays, if you’re … [+1569 chars]", "title": "Grab this Intel Core i5 mini PC with 24GB RAM on sale now for $319", "fullContent": "Nowadays, if you’re looking for a home office PC that can handle work and fun without taking up a bunch of space or costing a ton of money, you need to be thinking mini PCs. They offer better price-performance than laptops and are way smaller than desktop PCs. The Beelink EQI12 is a great example, especially now that it’s $319 on Amazon (was $389).\n\nThis particular model comes with an Intel Core i5-12450H processor and a solid 24GB of LPDDR5 RAM, a smooth combination that offers good performance and power efficiency without breaking the bank. It’s capable of running productivity apps, lots of browser tabs, and most other day-to-day tasks. And it’s rounded off with a 500GB M.2 SSD that offers plenty of storage space for your apps and files. If you feel the need to upgrade later, it’s bumpable up to 2x2TB drives.\n\nThe Beelink EQI12 is particularly great for home offices because it supports dual 4K monitors running at 60Hz each—more than enough screen real estate to fit all your apps. It’s not bad as far as connectivity is concerned either, with four USB-A ports, a USB-C port, two LAN ports, and a 3.5mm audio jack. Don’t forget Bluetooth 5.2 and Wi-Fi 6.\n\nSnag your very own Beelink EQI12 mini PC for $319 on Amazon, a real bargain price for the specs you get.\n\nSnag this Beelink mini PC for just $319 while you still can"}
{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-04-24T17:57:11Z", "url": "https://www.sammobile.com/news/android-16-one-ui-8-improve-parental-controls-supervision/", "publishedAt": "2025-04-24T17:57:11Z", "content": "The Google Discover feed, which appears on the leftmost home screen of Galaxy phones and tablets, is already hated by many. It shows the latest news articles, sports scores, and videos that users mig… [+1323 chars]", "title": "Google Discover could show even more useless content on your Galaxy phone", "fullContent": "Android 16 is coming soon, and we haven't seen many big design changes or groundbreaking features from the four beta updates that have been released. However, there might be one big feature that Google has kept under the wraps until now. A report reveals that Google might bring major improvements to parental controls for web content.\n\nAndroid 16 could get Family Link-powered parental ‘Supervision‘ controls for web content\n\nTo improve the Parental Controls feature on Android, Google seems to be developing a brand new menu called Supervision in the Settings app, and this was reported by Android Authority. It currently features two things: Use Device Supervision toggle and Web Content Filters.\n\nThe Use Device Supervision toggle is disabled by default. To enable it, you need to set a new PIN for the supervised account. Then, you can enter the Web Content Filters option. It allows all web content by default, but you can set it to block explicit content, including images, links, and text. Like most web content filtering systems, it might not block all explicit content.\n\nThis new section's description mentions “content restrictions & other limits,” which means Google might bring more options to it in the future. And that could be the reason why Google kept it hidden in all Android 16 beta releases. The fully baked version of the feature could be showcased with the stable release of Android 16.\n\nOne UI 8 could bring Supervision feature for better parental controls\n\nSamsung has already started working on One UI 8 (based on Android 16), and it could include these Parental Controls improvements. While One UI 7 brought improved parental controls, it doesn't have a Supervision option directly in the Settings app."}
